An enjoyable way to kill a lot of spare time. Historically accurate, great graphics, good replayability due to changing start positions. Complaints about the torpedoes' inaccuracy should open up a book and see how poorly US torpedoes performed in the early stages of World War II. NEEDS: Ships should start out of range of each other (except at night); CVE strikes should have lessened capability due to smaller amount of planes carried; nice if subs had sonar so they could judge distance and not waste torpedoes on ships too far away. Major battery killer; tablet gets very hot while playing.

An excellent game , provided you remember it is a tablet app of <100 MB and not a PC game.     Pros:  *Stunning, gorgeous visuals and beautiful ships.  *Well thought out surface combat; detailed modeling of ship buoyancy and gun combat.  * Addicting and fun.   Cons:  * ASW and air warfare is not impressive.  Submarines can only be attacked with gunfire (!) and cannot submerge below periscope depth. The traditional destroyer tactic of ramming a sub is impossible.  Dive bombing is too easy because the ship does not maneuver. Also, no fighters.    * All conflicts take place at the naval version of knife-fighting range, so it is possible for a destroyer to torpedo a battleship, or a battleship to mission-kill a carrier, on their first moves.  The most critical component of naval combat -- range -- is almost nonexistent.   * For this reason the most powerful unit in the game is the battleship, not the carrier. Like the carrier, the battleship has enough range to hit any target in the playing field.  Unlike the carrier, it remains fully functional at all times unless actually sunk.

replyContent: See page 9 of manual. US dud rate starts at 40% (historically US had estimated 80% in early war) which is reduced to 4% once you use your Renown to get the Improved Detonators upgrade. IJN dud rate starts at 4% as Japan had what was considered the best torpedoes of that era.

Otherwise it degrades into a wild guessing game.  Oh, and a final note to the developer: if you can re-skin this into a WW I Dreadnought battle game, I would gladly pay another $5.99. It's not hard to play,. and it's not stressful. There are no annoying in-app purchases. You pay for the game and that's it. The graphics are fantastic, with gunfire a payoff every turn, and the ships look like the real thing. The gameplay is turn-based, with simple maneuver and combat. The combat is what makes it fun. Aiming at the target is easy. The challenge is guessing the proper elevation. Your first shot may fall short. Next, you may be long, as you "bracket" the target. Markers show you where your shots have fallen to make aiming easier. What is satisfying is landing a salvo right on target. Ships don't take much damage, so games are not overlong. Lots of fun, but won't ramp you up before bedtime.
